</section>
<section id=3D"function-and-variable-names">
<h4><a class=3D"toc-backref" href=3D"https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/#func=
tion-and-variable-names" role=3D"doc-backlink">Function and Variable Names<=
/a></h4>
<p>Function names should be lowercase, with words separated by
underscores as necessary to improve readability.</p>
<p>Variable names follow the same convention as function names.</p>
<p>mixedCase is allowed only in contexts where that=E2=80=99s already the
prevailing style (e.g. threading.py), to retain backwards
compatibility.</p>
</section>
<section id=3D"function-and-method-arguments">
<h4><a class=3D"toc-backref" href=3D"https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/#func=
tion-and-method-arguments" role=3D"doc-backlink">Function and Method Argume=
nts</a></h4>
<p>Always use <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"p=
re">self</span></code> for the first argument to instance methods.</p>
<p>Always use <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"p=
re">cls</span></code> for the first argument to class methods.</p>
<p>If a function argument=E2=80=99s name clashes with a reserved keyword, i=
t is
generally better to append a single trailing underscore rather than
use an abbreviation or spelling corruption.  Thus <code class=3D"docutils l=
iteral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">class_</span></code> is better
than <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">clss<=
/span></code>.  (Perhaps better is to avoid such clashes by using a
synonym.)</p>
</section>
<section id=3D"method-names-and-instance-variables">
<h4><a class=3D"toc-backref" href=3D"https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/#meth=
od-names-and-instance-variables" role=3D"doc-backlink">Method Names and Ins=
tance Variables</a></h4>
<p>Use the function naming rules: lowercase with words separated by
underscores as necessary to improve readability.</p>
<p>Use one leading underscore only for non-public methods and instance
variables.</p>
<p>To avoid name clashes with subclasses, use two leading underscores to
invoke Python=E2=80=99s name mangling rules.</p>
<p>Python mangles these names with the class name: if class Foo has an
attribute named <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D=
"pre">__a</span></code>, it cannot be accessed by <code class=3D"docutils l=
iteral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">Foo.__a</span></code>.  (An
insistent user could still gain access by calling <code class=3D"docutils l=
iteral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">Foo._Foo__a</span></code>.)
Generally, double leading underscores should be used only to avoid
name conflicts with attributes in classes designed to be subclassed.</p>
<p>Note: there is some controversy about the use of __names (see below).</p=
>
</section>
<section id=3D"constants">
<h4><a class=3D"toc-backref" href=3D"https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/#cons=
tants" role=3D"doc-backlink">Constants</a></h4>
<p>Constants are usually defined on a module level and written in all
capital letters with underscores separating words.  Examples include
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">MAX_OVERFL=
OW</span></code> and <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span cla=
ss=3D"pre">TOTAL</span></code>.</p>
</section>
<section id=3D"designing-for-inheritance">
<h4><a class=3D"toc-backref" href=3D"https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/#desi=
gning-for-inheritance" role=3D"doc-backlink">Designing for Inheritance</a><=
/h4>
<p>Always decide whether a class=E2=80=99s methods and instance variables
(collectively: =E2=80=9Cattributes=E2=80=9D) should be public or non-public=
.  If in
doubt, choose non-public; it=E2=80=99s easier to make it public later than =
to
make a public attribute non-public.</p>
<p>Public attributes are those that you expect unrelated clients of your
class to use, with your commitment to avoid backwards incompatible
changes.  Non-public attributes are those that are not intended to be
used by third parties; you make no guarantees that non-public
attributes won=E2=80=99t change or even be removed.</p>
<p>We don=E2=80=99t use the term =E2=80=9Cprivate=E2=80=9D here, since no a=
ttribute is really
private in Python (without a generally unnecessary amount of work).</p>
<p>Another category of attributes are those that are part of the
=E2=80=9Csubclass API=E2=80=9D (often called =E2=80=9Cprotected=E2=80=9D in=
 other languages).  Some
classes are designed to be inherited from, either to extend or modify
aspects of the class=E2=80=99s behavior.  When designing such a class, take
care to make explicit decisions about which attributes are public,
which are part of the subclass API, and which are truly only to be
used by your base class.</p>
<p>With this in mind, here are the Pythonic guidelines:</p>
<ul>
<li>Public attributes should have no leading underscores.</li>
<li>If your public attribute name collides with a reserved keyword,
append a single trailing underscore to your attribute name.  This is
preferable to an abbreviation or corrupted spelling.  (However,
notwithstanding this rule, =E2=80=98cls=E2=80=99 is the preferred spelling =
for any
variable or argument which is known to be a class, especially the
first argument to a class method.)<p>Note 1: See the argument name recommen=
dation above for class methods.</p>
</li>
<li>For simple public data attributes, it is best to expose just the
attribute name, without complicated accessor/mutator methods.  Keep
in mind that Python provides an easy path to future enhancement,
should you find that a simple data attribute needs to grow
functional behavior.  In that case, use properties to hide
functional implementation behind simple data attribute access
syntax.<p>Note 1: Try to keep the functional behavior side-effect free,
although side-effects such as caching are generally fine.</p>
<p>Note 2: Avoid using properties for computationally expensive
operations; the attribute notation makes the caller believe that
access is (relatively) cheap.</p>
</li>
<li>If your class is intended to be subclassed, and you have attributes
that you do not want subclasses to use, consider naming them with
double leading underscores and no trailing underscores.  This
invokes Python=E2=80=99s name mangling algorithm, where the name of the
class is mangled into the attribute name.  This helps avoid
attribute name collisions should subclasses inadvertently contain
attributes with the same name.<p>Note 1: Note that only the simple class na=
me is used in the mangled
name, so if a subclass chooses both the same class name and attribute
name, you can still get name collisions.</p>
<p>Note 2: Name mangling can make certain uses, such as debugging and
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__getattr_=
_()</span></code>, less convenient.  However the name mangling
algorithm is well documented and easy to perform manually.</p>
<p>Note 3: Not everyone likes name mangling.  Try to balance the
need to avoid accidental name clashes with potential use by
advanced callers.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"public-and-internal-interfaces">
<h3><a class=3D"toc-backref" href=3D"https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/#publ=
ic-and-internal-interfaces" role=3D"doc-backlink">Public and Internal Inter=
faces</a></h3>
<p>Any backwards compatibility guarantees apply only to public interfaces.
Accordingly, it is important that users be able to clearly distinguish
between public and internal interfaces.</p>
<p>Documented interfaces are considered public, unless the documentation
explicitly declares them to be provisional or internal interfaces exempt
from the usual backwards compatibility guarantees. All undocumented
interfaces should be assumed to be internal.</p>
<p>To better support introspection, modules should explicitly declare the
names in their public API using the <code class=3D"docutils literal notrans=
late"><span class=3D"pre">__all__</span></code> attribute. Setting
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__all__</s=
pan></code> to an empty list indicates that the module has no public API.</=
p>
<p>Even with <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pr=
e">__all__</span></code> set appropriately, internal interfaces (packages,
modules, classes, functions, attributes or other names) should still be
prefixed with a single leading underscore.</p>
<p>An interface is also considered internal if any containing namespace
(package, module or class) is considered internal.</p>
<p>Imported names should always be considered an implementation detail.
Other modules must not rely on indirect access to such imported names
unless they are an explicitly documented part of the containing module=E2=
=80=99s
API, such as <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pr=
e">os.path</span></code> or a package=E2=80=99s <code class=3D"docutils lit=
eral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__init__</span></code> module that ex=
poses
functionality from submodules.</p>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"programming-recommendations">
<h2><a class=3D"toc-backref" href=3D"https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/#prog=
ramming-recommendations" role=3D"doc-backlink">Programming Recommendations<=
/a></h2>
<ul>
<li>Code should be written in a way that does not disadvantage other
implementations of Python (PyPy, Jython, IronPython, Cython, Psyco,
and such).<p>For example, do not rely on CPython=E2=80=99s efficient implem=
entation of
in-place string concatenation for statements in the form <code class=3D"doc=
utils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">a</span> <span class=3D"pre"=
>+=3D</span> <span class=3D"pre">b</span></code>
or <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">a</span=
> <span class=3D"pre">=3D</span> <span class=3D"pre">a</span> <span class=
=3D"pre">+</span> <span class=3D"pre">b</span></code>.  This optimization i=
s fragile even in CPython (it
only works for some types) and isn=E2=80=99t present at all in implementati=
ons
that don=E2=80=99t use refcounting.  In performance sensitive parts of the
library, the <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pr=
e">''.join()</span></code> form should be used instead.  This will
ensure that concatenation occurs in linear time across various
implementations.</p>
</li>
<li>Comparisons to singletons like None should always be done with
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">is</span><=
/code> or <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">=
is</span> <span class=3D"pre">not</span></code>, never the equality operato=
rs.<p>Also, beware of writing <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate">=
<span class=3D"pre">if</span> <span class=3D"pre">x</span></code> when you =
really mean <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre=
">if</span> <span class=3D"pre">x</span> <span class=3D"pre">is</span> <spa=
n class=3D"pre">not</span>
<span class=3D"pre">None</span></code> =E2=80=93 e.g. when testing whether =
a variable or argument that
defaults to None was set to some other value.  The other value might
have a type (such as a container) that could be false in a boolean
context!</p>
</li>
<li>Use <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">is=
</span> <span class=3D"pre">not</span></code> operator rather than <code cl=
ass=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">not</span> <span c=
lass=3D"pre">...</span> <span class=3D"pre">is</span></code>.  While both
expressions are functionally identical, the former is more readable
and preferred:<div class=3D"highlight-default notranslate"><div class=3D"hi=
ghlight"><pre><span></span><span class=3D"c1"># Correct:</span>
<span class=3D"k">if</span> <span class=3D"n">foo</span> <span class=3D"ow"=
>is</span> <span class=3D"ow">not</span> <span class=3D"kc">None</span><spa=
n class=3D"p">:</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<div class=3D"highlight-default notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight"><pre>=
<span></span><span class=3D"c1"># Wrong:</span>
<span class=3D"k">if</span> <span class=3D"ow">not</span> <span class=3D"n"=
>foo</span> <span class=3D"ow">is</span> <span class=3D"kc">None</span><spa=
n class=3D"p">:</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</li>
<li>When implementing ordering operations with rich comparisons, it is
best to implement all six operations (<code class=3D"docutils literal notra=
nslate"><span class=3D"pre">__eq__</span></code>, <code class=3D"docutils l=
iteral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__ne__</span></code>,
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__lt__</sp=
an></code>, <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre=
">__le__</span></code>, <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span =
class=3D"pre">__gt__</span></code>, <code class=3D"docutils literal notrans=
late"><span class=3D"pre">__ge__</span></code>) rather than relying
on other code to only exercise a particular comparison.<p>To minimize the e=
ffort involved, the <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span clas=
s=3D"pre">functools.total_ordering()</span></code>
decorator provides a tool to generate missing comparison methods.</p>
<p><a class=3D"pep reference internal" href=3D"https://peps.python.org/pep-=
0207" title=3D"PEP 207 =E2=80=93 Rich Comparisons">PEP 207</a> indicates th=
at reflexivity rules <em>are</em> assumed by Python.
Thus, the interpreter may swap <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"=
><span class=3D"pre">y</span> <span class=3D"pre">&gt;</span> <span class=
=3D"pre">x</span></code> with <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate">=
<span class=3D"pre">x</span> <span class=3D"pre">&lt;</span> <span class=3D=
"pre">y</span></code>, <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span c=
lass=3D"pre">y</span> <span class=3D"pre">&gt;=3D</span> <span class=3D"pre=
">x</span></code>
with <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">x</sp=
an> <span class=3D"pre">&lt;=3D</span> <span class=3D"pre">y</span></code>,=
 and may swap the arguments of <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"=
><span class=3D"pre">x</span> <span class=3D"pre">=3D=3D</span> <span class=
=3D"pre">y</span></code> and <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><=
span class=3D"pre">x</span> <span class=3D"pre">!=3D</span>
<span class=3D"pre">y</span></code>.  The <code class=3D"docutils literal n=
otranslate"><span class=3D"pre">sort()</span></code> and <code class=3D"doc=
utils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">min()</span></code> operatio=
ns are guaranteed to use
the <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">&lt;</=
span></code> operator and the <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate">=
<span class=3D"pre">max()</span></code> function uses the <code class=3D"do=
cutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">&gt;</span></code>
operator.  However, it is best to implement all six operations so
that confusion doesn=E2=80=99t arise in other contexts.</p>
</li>
<li>Always use a def statement instead of an assignment statement that bind=
s
a lambda expression directly to an identifier:<div class=3D"highlight-defau=
lt notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight"><pre><span></span><span class=3D"c=
1"># Correct:</span>
<span class=3D"k">def</span> <span class=3D"nf">f</span><span class=3D"p">(=
</span><span class=3D"n">x</span><span class=3D"p">):</span> <span class=3D=
"k">return</span> <span class=3D"mi">2</span><span class=3D"o">*</span><spa=
n class=3D"n">x</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<div class=3D"highlight-default notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight"><pre>=
<span></span><span class=3D"c1"># Wrong:</span>
<span class=3D"n">f</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=3D"k">l=
ambda</span> <span class=3D"n">x</span><span class=3D"p">:</span> <span cla=
ss=3D"mi">2</span><span class=3D"o">*</span><span class=3D"n">x</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<p>The first form means that the name of the resulting function object is
specifically =E2=80=98f=E2=80=99 instead of the generic =E2=80=98&lt;lambda=
&gt;=E2=80=99. This is more
useful for tracebacks and string representations in general. The use
of the assignment statement eliminates the sole benefit a lambda
expression can offer over an explicit def statement (i.e. that it can
be embedded inside a larger expression)</p>
</li>
<li>Derive exceptions from <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><sp=
an class=3D"pre">Exception</span></code> rather than <code class=3D"docutil=
s literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">BaseException</span></code>.
Direct inheritance from <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span =
class=3D"pre">BaseException</span></code> is reserved for exceptions
where catching them is almost always the wrong thing to do.<p>Design except=
ion hierarchies based on the distinctions that code
<em>catching</em> the exceptions is likely to need, rather than the locatio=
ns
where the exceptions are raised. Aim to answer the question
=E2=80=9CWhat went wrong?=E2=80=9D programmatically, rather than only stati=
ng that
=E2=80=9CA problem occurred=E2=80=9D (see <a class=3D"pep reference interna=
l" href=3D"https://peps.python.org/pep-3151" title=3D"PEP 3151 =E2=80=93 Re=
working the OS and IO exception hierarchy">PEP 3151</a> for an example of t=
his lesson being
learned for the builtin exception hierarchy)</p>
<p>Class naming conventions apply here, although you should add the
suffix =E2=80=9CError=E2=80=9D to your exception classes if the exception i=
s an
error.  Non-error exceptions that are used for non-local flow control
or other forms of signaling need no special suffix.</p>
</li>
<li>Use exception chaining appropriately. <code class=3D"docutils literal n=
otranslate"><span class=3D"pre">raise</span> <span class=3D"pre">X</span> <=
span class=3D"pre">from</span> <span class=3D"pre">Y</span></code>
should be used to indicate explicit replacement without losing the
original traceback.<p>When deliberately replacing an inner exception (using=
 <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">raise</sp=
an> <span class=3D"pre">X</span> <span class=3D"pre">from</span>
<span class=3D"pre">None</span></code>), ensure that relevant details are t=
ransferred to the new
exception (such as preserving the attribute name when converting
KeyError to AttributeError, or embedding the text of the original
exception in the new exception message).</p>
</li>
<li>When catching exceptions, mention specific exceptions whenever
possible instead of using a bare <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslat=
e"><span class=3D"pre">except:</span></code> clause:<div class=3D"highlight=
-default notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight"><pre><span></span><span clas=
s=3D"k">try</span><span class=3D"p">:</span>
    <span class=3D"kn">import</span> <span class=3D"nn">platform_specific_m=
odule</span>
<span class=3D"k">except</span> <span class=3D"ne">ImportError</span><span =
class=3D"p">:</span>
    <span class=3D"n">platform_specific_module</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D=
</span> <span class=3D"kc">None</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<p>A bare <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">=
except:</span></code> clause will catch SystemExit and
KeyboardInterrupt exceptions, making it harder to interrupt a
program with Control-C, and can disguise other problems.  If you
want to catch all exceptions that signal program errors, use
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">except</sp=
an> <span class=3D"pre">Exception:</span></code> (bare except is equivalent=
 to <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">except=
</span>
<span class=3D"pre">BaseException:</span></code>).</p>
<p>A good rule of thumb is to limit use of bare =E2=80=98except=E2=80=99 cl=
auses to two
cases:</p>
<ol class=3D"arabic simple">
<li>If the exception handler will be printing out or logging the
traceback; at least the user will be aware that an error has
occurred.</li>
<li>If the code needs to do some cleanup work, but then lets the
exception propagate upwards with <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslat=
e"><span class=3D"pre">raise</span></code>.  <code class=3D"docutils litera=
l notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">try...finally</span></code>
can be a better way to handle this case.</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>When catching operating system errors, prefer the explicit exception
hierarchy introduced in Python 3.3 over introspection of <code class=3D"doc=
utils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">errno</span></code>
values.</li>
<li>Additionally, for all try/except clauses, limit the <code class=3D"docu=
tils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">try</span></code> clause
to the absolute minimum amount of code necessary.  Again, this
avoids masking bugs:<div class=3D"highlight-default notranslate"><div class=
=3D"highlight"><pre><span></span><span class=3D"c1"># Correct:</span>
<span class=3D"k">try</span><span class=3D"p">:</span>
    <span class=3D"n">value</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=
=3D"n">collection</span><span class=3D"p">[</span><span class=3D"n">key</sp=
an><span class=3D"p">]</span>
<span class=3D"k">except</span> <span class=3D"ne">KeyError</span><span cla=
ss=3D"p">:</span>
    <span class=3D"k">return</span> <span class=3D"n">key_not_found</span><=
span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">key</span><span class=3D"p">)</s=
pan>
<span class=3D"k">else</span><span class=3D"p">:</span>
    <span class=3D"k">return</span> <span class=3D"n">handle_value</span><s=
pan class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">value</span><span class=3D"p">)</=
span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<div class=3D"highlight-default notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight"><pre>=
<span></span><span class=3D"c1"># Wrong:</span>
<span class=3D"k">try</span><span class=3D"p">:</span>
    <span class=3D"c1"># Too broad!</span>
    <span class=3D"k">return</span> <span class=3D"n">handle_value</span><s=
pan class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">collection</span><span class=3D"p=
">[</span><span class=3D"n">key</span><span class=3D"p">])</span>
<span class=3D"k">except</span> <span class=3D"ne">KeyError</span><span cla=
ss=3D"p">:</span>
    <span class=3D"c1"># Will also catch KeyError raised by handle_value()<=
/span>
    <span class=3D"k">return</span> <span class=3D"n">key_not_found</span><=
span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">key</span><span class=3D"p">)</s=
pan>
</pre></div>
</div>
</li>
<li>When a resource is local to a particular section of code, use a
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">with</span=
></code> statement to ensure it is cleaned up promptly and reliably
after use. A try/finally statement is also acceptable.</li>
<li>Context managers should be invoked through separate functions or method=
s
whenever they do something other than acquire and release resources:<div cl=
ass=3D"highlight-default notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight"><pre><span><=
/span><span class=3D"c1"># Correct:</span>
<span class=3D"k">with</span> <span class=3D"n">conn</span><span class=3D"o=
">.</span><span class=3D"n">begin_transaction</span><span class=3D"p">():</=
span>
    <span class=3D"n">do_stuff_in_transaction</span><span class=3D"p">(</sp=
an><span class=3D"n">conn</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<div class=3D"highlight-default notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight"><pre>=
<span></span><span class=3D"c1"># Wrong:</span>
<span class=3D"k">with</span> <span class=3D"n">conn</span><span class=3D"p=
">:</span>
    <span class=3D"n">do_stuff_in_transaction</span><span class=3D"p">(</sp=
an><span class=3D"n">conn</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<p>The latter example doesn=E2=80=99t provide any information to indicate t=
hat
the <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__ente=
r__</span></code> and <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span cl=
ass=3D"pre">__exit__</span></code> methods are doing something other
than closing the connection after a transaction.  Being explicit is
important in this case.</p>
</li>
<li>Be consistent in return statements.  Either all return statements in
a function should return an expression, or none of them should.  If
any return statement returns an expression, any return statements
where no value is returned should explicitly state this as <code class=3D"d=
ocutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">return</span>
<span class=3D"pre">None</span></code>, and an explicit return statement sh=
ould be present at the
end of the function (if reachable):<div class=3D"highlight-default notransl=
ate"><div class=3D"highlight"><pre><span></span><span class=3D"c1"># Correc=
t:</span>

<span class=3D"k">def</span> <span class=3D"nf">foo</span><span class=3D"p"=
>(</span><span class=3D"n">x</span><span class=3D"p">):</span>
    <span class=3D"k">if</span> <span class=3D"n">x</span> <span class=3D"o=
">&gt;=3D</span> <span class=3D"mi">0</span><span class=3D"p">:</span>
        <span class=3D"k">return</span> <span class=3D"n">math</span><span =
class=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">sqrt</span><span class=3D"p">(</span>=
<span class=3D"n">x</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
    <span class=3D"k">else</span><span class=3D"p">:</span>
        <span class=3D"k">return</span> <span class=3D"kc">None</span>

<span class=3D"k">def</span> <span class=3D"nf">bar</span><span class=3D"p"=
>(</span><span class=3D"n">x</span><span class=3D"p">):</span>
    <span class=3D"k">if</span> <span class=3D"n">x</span> <span class=3D"o=
">&lt;</span> <span class=3D"mi">0</span><span class=3D"p">:</span>
        <span class=3D"k">return</span> <span class=3D"kc">None</span>
    <span class=3D"k">return</span> <span class=3D"n">math</span><span clas=
s=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">sqrt</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><spa=
n class=3D"n">x</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<div class=3D"highlight-default notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight"><pre>=
<span></span><span class=3D"c1"># Wrong:</span>

<span class=3D"k">def</span> <span class=3D"nf">foo</span><span class=3D"p"=
>(</span><span class=3D"n">x</span><span class=3D"p">):</span>
    <span class=3D"k">if</span> <span class=3D"n">x</span> <span class=3D"o=
">&gt;=3D</span> <span class=3D"mi">0</span><span class=3D"p">:</span>
        <span class=3D"k">return</span> <span class=3D"n">math</span><span =
class=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">sqrt</span><span class=3D"p">(</span>=
<span class=3D"n">x</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>

<span class=3D"k">def</span> <span class=3D"nf">bar</span><span class=3D"p"=
>(</span><span class=3D"n">x</span><span class=3D"p">):</span>
    <span class=3D"k">if</span> <span class=3D"n">x</span> <span class=3D"o=
">&lt;</span> <span class=3D"mi">0</span><span class=3D"p">:</span>
